{
  "query": "What are the documented outcomes of using different legal protection strategies, such as protecting primate species versus protecting their habitat?",
  "relevant_summary": "Documented outcomes for legally protecting primate species include: a population increase in rhesus macaques in India following an export ban over 17 years (before-and-after) [1524]; population declines in legally protected primate populations in Thailand and India alongside other interventions (two studies) [1524]; high mortality of introduced M\u00fcller\u2019s Bornean gibbons in Malaysia despite legal protection and other interventions (before-and-after) [1524]; and drill populations declining at four of five Cameroonian sites but increasing at one, despite legal protection (site comparison) [1524]. Documented outcomes for legally protecting primate habitat include: increases or cessation of killings of rhesus and grey snub-nosed monkeys in China after areas were protected with other interventions (review) [1578]; decreases in Tana River red colobus and crested mangabey numbers in Kenya despite protection (before-and-after) [1578]; a 34% increase in Hainan gibbons over nine years after protection in China (before-and-after) [1578]; most reintroduced golden lion tamarins not surviving over seven years in a protected area in Brazil, though reproduction partly compensated adult mortality (before-and-after) [1578]; most reintroduced central chimpanzees and lowland gorillas surviving 4\u20135 years after release into protected areas in the Republic of Congo and Gabon (two before-and-after studies) [1578]; and black howler monkeys in Mexican protected areas showing lower stress levels than those in unprotected fragments (controlled, site comparison) [1578]. Broader evidence on legally protecting habitats (not limited to primates) reports population increases and more positive trends in protected habitats in Europe (four studies, two replicated), extensive use of nature reserves by cranes in China (review), and mixed bird responses in Argentina with some guilds showing higher species richness or densities in protected forests and some no differences (replicated, randomised, controlled) [158]. Evidence for creating buffer zones around protected primate habitat is currently absent (\u201cno evidence\u201d identified) [1577].",
