{
  "query": "What are the effects of implementing veterinary and health-related interventions for wild or reintroduced primate populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across studies of reintroduced or translocated primates, pre-release veterinary screening was associated with mixed outcomes: most reintroduced golden lion tamarins did not survive over seven years, whereas most black lion tamarins survived over four months; 90% of reintroduced M\u00fcller\u2019s Bornean gibbons did not survive, but reintroduced Bornean agile gibbons behaved similarly to wild gibbons; most translocated orangutans survived translocation and the first three months post-translocation; most reintroduced chimpanzees survived over 1\u20135 years, though one reintroduced chimpanzee repeatedly returned to human settlements; other primates in multiple countries mostly survived at least four months or increased in population size, while several studies reported most animals died post-release; one population of translocated olive baboons survived 16 years post-translocation (1553). Continuous health monitoring with a permanent on-site veterinarian was associated with a 168% increase in the mountain gorilla population over 41 years, alongside other interventions (1554). Quarantine prior to release showed variable effects: most reintroduced golden lion tamarins and black-and-white ruffed lemurs did not survive over multi-year periods; one reintroduced chimpanzee repeatedly returned to human settlements; a reintroduced orangutan population decreased by 33% over 40 years, though all quarantined orangutans in one study survived over three months; over 80% of quarantined, reintroduced gorillas survived over ten years; most reintroduced lorises either died or their radio signal was lost (1541).",
